FBIS4-57883 "drlat102_t_94009" FBIS-LAT-94-102 Daily Report 25 May 1994 Venezuela Interior Minister on Speculation, Fight Against Crime Interior Minister on Speculation, Fight Against Crime PA2605030994 Caracas Union Radio Network in Spanish 2200 GMT 25 May 94 PA2605030994 Caracas Union Radio Network Spanish BFN [Report by Vicente Briceno at Miraflores Palace from the "Union Radio News" newscast] [Text] Interior Minister Ramon Escovar Salom has issued an appeal to the people, urging them to remain alert and report the speculation and hoarding that is currently taking place with food and medicine. The control mechanisms' inability to curb this abuse, which negatively affects the consumer spending, has compelled the government to (?seek) ways to control unscrupulous businessmen who want to profit from the current crisis in the country. Likewise, the interior minister said he is willing to hear the community's proposals to cooperate with police authorities in the struggle against crime. He referred to the initiative adopted by the [word indistinct] Against Crime Movement, which he received in his office, [words indistinct] plan actions to fight crime. [Begin Escovar recording] I wish to welcome, as interior minister, these spontaneous movements organized by civilian society, which realizes personal safety is the country's leading problem. Some polls show the safety problem is the country's leading problem -- 58 percent of Venezuelans believe this is the leading problem in the country. This proves the democratic maturity many people have because they realize they must cooperate and mobilize themselves against violence and crime. The government is [words indistinct]. [end recording] The interior minister explained that these groups organized as civic movements (?advocate) defending themselves with precautionary measures rather than weapons; although [words indistinct] permits, provided they fulfill the provisions demanded by the weapons and explosives law.
